{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.11,0.54,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents for evaluation of abnormal liver function tests. He does not smoke or drink alcohol, and hepatitis screening is negative. His only significant medical history is inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his liver disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency","Haemochromatosis","Primary biliary cholangitis","Primary sclerosing cholangitis","Wilson disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s abnormal liver function tests is \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary sclerosing cholangitis. \u003C/strong\u003EThis condition has a strong association with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis, occurring in up to 5% of these patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a hereditary condition causing iron overload, but has no specific association with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD). \u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary biliary cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E predominantly affects women and is not associated with IBD. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the lungs and liver but has no association with IBD. \u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of copper metabolism that typically presents at a younger age and has no association with IBD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst all of the listed conditions are known to have an association with liver disease, in this situation of a case of known IBD, primary sclerosing cholangitis is the most likely explanation for his abnormal liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary sclerosing cholangitis has a strong association with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis.","Primary sclerosing cholangitis is characterised by progressive inflammation and fibrosis of intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Ed